// PHASE 10: Ethics, Law & Dubai Health Regulations (100 Questions)
const phase10 = {
  phase: 10, title: "Ethics, Law & Dubai Health Regulations", icon: "⚖️", color: "#2c3e50",
  questions: [
    { id:"p10q1", question:"The Dubai Health Authority (DHA) is the regulatory body responsible for:", options:["Only private hospitals in Dubai","All healthcare services, facilities, and professionals in the Emirate of Dubai","Only public hospitals","Only pharmaceutical regulation"], answer:1, explanation:"DHA regulates all healthcare services in Dubai: licensing healthcare professionals, accrediting facilities, setting standards, enforcing regulations, and developing health policy for all (public and private) healthcare entities in Dubai." },
    { id:"p10q2", question:"To practice nursing in Dubai (DHA), a foreign nurse must:", options:["Only have a degree from any country","Obtain DHA license: verify credentials (DataFlow primary source verification), pass DHA licensing exam, meet CPD requirements","Practice without any licensure initially","Only register with their home country's nursing board"], answer:1, explanation:"DHA nursing licensure: educational credential verification (DataFlow), pass DHA competency exam (nursing), good standing certificate, pass medical fitness, Emirates ID, provide malpractice/liability insurance. License valid 2 years then renewed." },
    { id:"p10q3", question:"The four principles of biomedical ethics (Beauchamp and Childress) are:", options:["Beneficence, Justice, Fidelity, Veracity","Autonomy, Beneficence, Non-maleficence, Justice","Paternalism, Advocacy, Truth-telling, Care","Respect, Empathy, Trust, Fairness"], answer:1, explanation:"Principlism (Beauchamp & Childress): 1)Autonomy (patient's right to make decisions), 2)Beneficence (do good), 3)Non-maleficence ('First do no harm' — primum non nocere), 4)Justice (fair distribution of resources/burdens). Foundation of biomedical ethics." },
    { id:"p10q4", question:"Informed consent requires:", options:["Only patient's signature","Patient with decision-making capacity receives adequate information (diagnosis, treatment, risks, benefits, alternatives), understands it, and voluntarily agrees","Family consent only","Verbal consent always sufficient"], answer:1, explanation:"Valid informed consent: Disclosure (adequate information), Comprehension (patient understands), Voluntariness (free from coercion), Capacity (decision-making ability). Without capacity: surrogate decision-maker or advance directive guides decisions." },
    { id:"p10q5", question:"In the UAE, the Patient Rights Law (Federal Law No. 4 of 2016) includes the right to:", options:["Only emergency care","Receive quality care, be informed, provide consent, confidentiality, refuse treatment, access medical records, dignity, and non-discrimination","Only choose their doctor","Access care only in emergency"], answer:1, explanation:"UAE Federal Law 4/2016 (Medical Liability): patients' rights: quality care, informed consent, confidentiality, access to records, refuse treatment (competent adult), second opinion, complaint mechanism, dignity and respect, non-discrimination." },
    { id:"p10q6", question:"Mandatory reporting in UAE healthcare is required for:", options:["All patient diagnoses","Communicable/notifiable diseases, suspected child abuse, gunshot wounds, occupational injuries, and certain medical conditions affecting driving/flying ability","Only infectious diseases","Only crimes"], answer:1, explanation:"UAE mandatory reporting: notifiable infectious diseases (to MOHAP/DHA), child abuse (Federal Law 3/2016 — Wadeema's Law), domestic violence, gunshot wounds, occupational injuries, medical fitness concerns for pilots/drivers. Failure to report is punishable." },
    { id:"p10q7", question:"A DHA-licensed nurse accidentally administers wrong medication causing patient harm. This is classified as:", options:["Criminal negligence always","Medical error — reported through facility incident reporting system; may lead to DHA investigation and disciplinary action","Minor issue with no consequences","Only a hospital management issue"], answer:1, explanation:"Medical error management in Dubai: report through facility's incident reporting system (non-punitive culture encouraged), root cause analysis, DHA may investigate. UAE Medical Liability Law 4/2016: compensation for malpractice. Criminal liability if gross negligence proven." },
    { id:"p10q8", question:"Patient confidentiality can be breached in UAE healthcare:", options:["Never — absolute right","When required by law (notifiable diseases, court orders), public health necessity, or with patient consent","Whenever medically convenient","Whenever family members request it"], answer:1, explanation:"Confidentiality exceptions (UAE): 1) Law requires disclosure (notifiable diseases, court orders), 2) Imminent danger to self or others, 3) Patient consent to share. UAE Law 2/2019 (Data Protection): health data is special category requiring explicit consent for sharing." },
    { id:"p10q9", question:"Do Not Resuscitate (DNR) orders in UAE:", options:["Are not recognized legally","Must be documented in medical record, require informed consent, physician order, and regular review — family alone cannot issue DNR","Are issued by family only","Apply automatically after age 70"], answer:1, explanation:"DNR orders in UAE: physician-ordered, patient/legal guardian informed consent required, documented in medical record, time-limited (reviewed regularly). DNR does not mean no treatment — only that CPR is withheld. Islamic ethical considerations are integrated." },
    { id:"p10q10", question:"The DHA's Jawda initiative is focused on:", options:["Facility construction","Quality and patient safety — healthcare quality improvement programs, accreditation, and safety standards in Dubai","Staff recruitment","Only pharmaceutical regulation"], answer:1, explanation:"DHA Jawda ('quality' in Arabic): dedicated to quality improvement and patient safety in Dubai's healthcare sector. Oversees accreditation, quality standards, patient safety initiatives, reporting systems, and healthcare performance indicators." },
    { id:"p10q11", question:"Which principle means 'first, do no harm'?", options:["Autonomy","Beneficence","Non-maleficence — primum non nocere","Justice"], answer:2, explanation:"Non-maleficence: the obligation to avoid causing harm. From Hippocratic tradition: 'primum non nocere' (first, do no harm). Applied in weighing risk-benefit of treatments — harm must be proportionate to expected benefit." },
    { id:"p10q12", question:"A nurse witnesses a colleague falsifying patient records. The CORRECT action is:", options:["Ignore it — not your concern","Confront the colleague personally and resolve internally","Report to nurse manager/supervisor immediately — patient safety is at risk","Document in own personal diary only"], answer:2, explanation:"Falsifying medical records: serious breach of professional, ethical, and legal obligations. Patient safety issue. Nurse must report through proper channels: supervisor, risk management, quality department. Failure to report may implicate the witnessing nurse. DHA licensing at risk." },
    { id:"p10q13", question:"Beneficence in nursing practice means:", options:["Doing what the nurse thinks is best, ignoring patient preference","Acting in the patient's best interest — promoting good, preventing harm while respecting autonomy","Never causing any discomfort","Following only doctor's orders"], answer:1, explanation:"Beneficence: positive obligation to act in patient's best interest. Differs from paternalism (overriding patient preferences 'for their own good'). Balanced with autonomy: patient has right to refuse beneficial treatment. Beneficence includes preventing harm." },
    { id:"p10q14", question:"The ethical principle of 'Justice' in healthcare relates to:", options:["Legal punishment for errors","Fair and equitable distribution of healthcare resources and treatment — giving each what they are due","Punishing wrongdoers","Legal compliance only"], answer:1, explanation:"Justice: fairness in distribution of benefits and burdens. Healthcare justice: equitable access to care regardless of ability to pay, race, gender, nationality. Distributive justice: how resources are allocated. Procedural justice: fair processes." },
    { id:"p10q15", question:"In UAE, a mentally competent adult patient refuses a blood transfusion for religious reasons. The nurse should:", options:["Administer the transfusion — it is life-saving","Respect the patient's autonomous decision — document informed refusal, ensure they understand consequences, continue supportive care","Force the transfusion after family consent","Discharge the patient immediately"], answer:1, explanation:"Patient autonomy: a competent adult has the absolute right to refuse any treatment, even life-saving treatment (e.g., Jehovah's Witness refusing blood). Document: informed refusal, capacity assessment, information given. Continue all other care." },
    { id:"p10q16", question:"Which document expresses a patient's healthcare wishes in advance (when they lose capacity)?", options:["Power of attorney only","Advance directive (living will) — states preferences for end-of-life care, specific treatments","Medical record","Insurance card"], answer:1, explanation:"Advance directive (living will): legal document stating patient's healthcare preferences (CPR, mechanical ventilation, artificial nutrition, organ donation) should they become incapacitated. UAE: limited formal advance directive legal framework but recognized ethically." },
    { id:"p10q17", question:"The nurse's legal duty of care requires:", options:["Only performing tasks exactly as instructed","Providing the standard of care a reasonably competent nurse in the same position would provide — failure = negligence","Perfection in all nursing acts","Only following physician orders"], answer:1, explanation:"Duty of care: nurses owe a legal duty to patients in their care. Breach = failure to meet the standard of a reasonable, competent nurse. If breach causes harm = negligence (basis for malpractice claims). 4 elements: duty, breach, causation, harm (4 D's: Duty, Dereliction, Direct cause, Damage)." },
    { id:"p10q18", question:"Veracity as a nursing ethical principle means:", options:["Protecting patient privacy","Being truthful — telling patients the truth about their diagnosis, prognosis, and care","Acting in patient's best interest","Keeping patient information confidential"], answer:1, explanation:"Veracity: obligation to be truthful. Truthfulness about diagnosis (even terminal), prognosis, treatment options. Deception or withholding important information violates veracity and autonomy. Cultural considerations (some cultures prefer family-mediated disclosure) are navigated carefully." },
    { id:"p10q19", question:"The legal concept of 'res ipsa loquitur' in medical malpractice means:", options:["The patient is always right","'The thing speaks for itself' — negligence is obvious without expert testimony (e.g., sponge left inside patient)","Double documentation required","Two witnesses needed for consent"], answer:1, explanation:"Res ipsa loquitur: 'the thing speaks for itself.' Applied when negligence is so obvious that expert testimony is unnecessary (retained surgical instrument, wrong-site surgery, wrong patient surgery). Negligence presumed — burden shifts to defendant." },
    { id:"p10q20", question:"DHA licensing exam for nurses evaluates:", options:["Only clinical skills","Clinical knowledge, professional standards, UAE health regulations, ethics, and nursing competencies — based on international nursing standards","Only pharmacology knowledge","Only medical diagnosis"], answer:1, explanation:"DHA nursing exam: tests clinical nursing competencies (medical-surgical, pharmacology, maternal-child, psychiatry, critical care), professional and ethical standards, UAE health regulations, and communication skills. Multiple-choice questions (300 for registration, 150 for re-examination)." },
    { id:"p10q21", question:"Negligence in nursing practice is defined as:", options:["Any medication error","Failure to provide the standard of care a reasonably prudent nurse would provide, resulting in patient harm","Any deviation from routine","Any unintended outcome"], answer:1, explanation:"Nursing negligence: deviation from accepted standard of care → patient harm. Elements: 1)Nurse owed duty of care, 2)Duty was breached (below standard), 3)Breach directly caused harm, 4)Patient suffered measurable damage." },
    { id:"p10q22", question:"In Dubai, healthcare facilities must be licensed by:", options:["Ministry of Health only","DHA (Dubai Health Authority) — all facilities (hospitals, clinics, pharmacies) must be DHA licensed and inspected","Any international accreditation body","The individual hospital's governing board"], answer:1, explanation:"DHA regulates all healthcare facilities in Dubai: hospitals, specialty clinics, GP clinics, dental clinics, pharmacies, laboratories, radiology centers. Facilities must meet DHA standards, undergo regular inspection, and maintain accreditation (JCI, ACHS, or DHA approved)." },
    { id:"p10q23", question:"Cultural competence in nursing practice means:", options:["Treating all patients identically regardless of background","Understanding, respecting, and appropriately responding to patients' cultural beliefs, values, and practices that affect their health and healthcare","Ignoring cultural differences to be fair","Only learning Arabic as a nurse in UAE"], answer:1, explanation:"Cultural competence: nurses in UAE work with patients from 200+ nationalities. Essential: awareness of own cultural bias, knowledge of diverse cultural practices affecting health (diet, gender interactions, religious practices, modesty, family decision-making), respect for difference." },
    { id:"p10q24", question:"A patient's family asks the nurse not to tell the patient their cancer diagnosis. The nurse should:", options:["Agree to keep information from the patient","Explain that the patient has the right to receive their own health information — work with physician and family to sensitively disclose following patient's wishes","Tell the patient immediately without physician involvement","Document and ignore the family's concern"], answer:1, explanation:"Truth-telling dilemma: patient's right to know vs. family's protective instinct. In UAE's diverse cultural context: assess patient's own wishes about information disclosure first. If patient wants information → provide it. Work with healthcare team and cultural mediators. Never lie to a patient who asks directly." },
    { id:"p10q25", question:"Scope of practice for registered nurses in DHA regulated settings includes:", options:["Any medical procedure without supervision","Comprehensive nursing assessment, planning, implementation, and evaluation; medication administration; health education; within licensed competencies — excludes physician-specific acts","Medical diagnosis only","Only basic care tasks"], answer:1, explanation:"RN scope of practice (DHA): assessment, nursing diagnosis, care planning, interventions (medication administration, procedures as per competency), evaluation, health education, case management, referral, supervision of LPNs/assistants. Cannot: independently prescribe, perform surgery, make medical diagnoses." },
    { id:"p10q26", question:"The UAE Anti-Narcotics Law is significant for nurses because:", options:["Nurses can freely prescribe narcotics","Controlled substances require strict documentation, double-checking, secure storage, and reporting of discrepancies — violations are criminal offenses in UAE","Narcotics are not used in UAE hospitals","Only pharmacists are responsible"], answer:1, explanation:"UAE Drug Regulations (Federal Law 14/1995): controlled substances require two-nurse verification for counting and administration, secure locked storage, discrepancy immediate reporting, physician prescription required. Criminal penalties for misuse/diversion." },
    { id:"p10q27", question:"What is 'whistleblowing' in the healthcare context?", options:["Excessive use of call light by patients","Reporting unsafe conditions, illegal activities, or serious ethical violations within an organization to appropriate authorities — legally protected in some jurisdictions","Calling emergency services","Alerting patients of discharge"], answer:1, explanation:"Whistleblowing: reporting concerns about patient safety, illegal activities, or serious misconduct through proper channels (internal first, then external regulatory bodies if unresolved). UAE DHA has a patient safety reporting system. Retaliation against whistleblowers is prohibited." },
    { id:"p10q28", question:"The right of a child (under 18 in UAE) to consent to treatment:", options:["Children cannot consent to anything","Requires parental/guardian consent for major decisions — mature minors may consent to minor procedures; emergency treatment given without consent when parents unavailable","Children over 14 can fully consent to all treatment","Parents have no say once child is 12"], answer:1, explanation:"Minor consent in UAE: generally requires parental/guardian consent. Emergency treatment: provided without consent if parents unavailable and delay would harm child. Mature minor doctrine: not codified in UAE law as in some Western countries. Court orders override parental refusal of life-saving treatment." },
    { id:"p10q29", question:"Triage in the emergency department follows which ethical principle?", options:["First come, first served always","Justice (fair allocation of resources based on medical need — greatest benefit, most urgent served first)","Autonomy alone","Beneficence only"], answer:1, explanation:"ED triage: applies distributive justice — resources allocated based on medical urgency and potential benefit, not on ability to pay, social status, or arrival time. Manchester Triage System (MTS) or similar: Immediate (Red) → Very Urgent (Orange) → Urgent (Yellow) → Standard (Green) → Non-Urgent (Blue)." },
    { id:"p10q30", question:"Medical records in UAE must be kept for a minimum of:", options:["2 years","5 years","10 years (for adults) and 10 years after reaching age of majority for children — or longer depending on facility policy","25 years"], answer:2, explanation:"UAE MOHAP/DHA regulations: medical records must be retained for minimum 10 years from last patient contact (adults); for children, 10 years after reaching age of majority (18 years). Electronic records must be equally secure. Longer retention for specialized cases." },
    { id:"p10q31", question:"Conflict of interest in healthcare occurs when:", options:["A nurse works two shifts","A healthcare professional's personal interests (financial, personal, research) interfere with their professional duty to the patient","A nurse disagrees with a physician","Different departments have scheduling conflicts"], answer:1, explanation:"Conflict of interest: personal interests (financial gain from drug company, research goals, personal relationships) bias clinical decision-making. Examples: accepting gifts from pharmaceutical companies, referring patients to own businesses. DHA has anti-corruption policies." },
    { id:"p10q32", question:"What does 'advocacy' mean in nursing?", options:["Telling patients what to do","Acting on behalf of patients — speaking up for their rights, needs, and preferences when they cannot do so themselves","Making all decisions for patients","Advocating for hospital policies only"], answer:1, explanation:"Nursing advocacy: fundamental nursing role. Includes: informing patients of rights, supporting informed decision-making, protecting patients from harm, ensuring voice of patient is heard by healthcare team, addressing inequities in care." },
    { id:"p10q33", question:"An advance directive in UAE must:", options:["Be witnessed by 10 people","Be notarized and registered to be legally binding — oral advance directives have limited legal standing","Be automatically followed without physician review","Override all clinical decisions"], answer:1, explanation:"UAE advance directives: legal framework is developing. Written directives with proper documentation carry more weight. Physicians and healthcare teams must use clinical judgment and consider patient wishes, family input, and Islamic principles in end-of-life decisions." },
    { id:"p10q34", question:"The Dubai Ambulance Corporation (DAC) operates under:", options:["DHA","Dubai Corporation for Ambulance Services (DCAS) — manages EMS and emergency response for Dubai","Only private companies","MOHAP directly"], answer:1, explanation:"Dubai Corporation for Ambulance Services (DCAS): responsible for pre-hospital emergency medical services in Dubai. Operates advanced and basic life support ambulances. Works in coordination with DHA-regulated hospitals and DCD (Dubai Civil Defence)." },
    { id:"p10q35", question:"A nurse receiving a telephone order from a physician should:", options:["Write it down and implement immediately without verification","Repeat the order back (read-back), verify, document 'T.O. Dr. [Name] per nurse [Name],' and have physician sign within 24 hours","Refuse all telephone orders","Only accept written orders"], answer:1, explanation:"Telephone/verbal orders: use SBAR communication, write down immediately, read back to verify (closed-loop communication), document 'T.O.' (telephone order) with prescribing physician's name and nurse's name. Physician must co-sign within prescribed time (24 hours per most policies)." },
    { id:"p10q36", question:"The ethical concept of 'paternalism' in healthcare refers to:", options:["Treating patients like family","Overriding patient autonomy 'for their own good' — deciding what is best for patients without their input","Parental consent for minors","Treating all patients equally"], answer:1, explanation:"Paternalism: healthcare provider makes decisions for patients based on provider's values of what is 'best' — overriding patient preferences. 'Hard' paternalism: override even when patient is competent. 'Soft' paternalism: intervene when capacity is impaired. Generally considered ethically problematic." },
    { id:"p10q37", question:"Which international accreditation body accredits many UAE hospitals?", options:["Only local UAE accreditation","Joint Commission International (JCI) — international branch of JCAHO (USA)","WHO certification","Only DHA accreditation"], answer:1, explanation:"JCI (Joint Commission International): accredits hospitals outside the US. Many Dubai hospitals hold JCI accreditation as mark of quality (e.g., American Hospital Dubai, Mediclinic, Cleveland Clinic Abu Dhabi). ACHS (Australian) and CCHSA (Canadian) also used in UAE." },
    { id:"p10q38", question:"Which principle supports allocating scarce ICU resources during a pandemic?", options:["First come, first served only","Utilitarian principle — maximize benefit to greatest number; also fair innings and life-cycle principles guide resource allocation","Willingness to pay determines access","Random lottery only"], answer:1, explanation:"Pandemic resource allocation ethics: utilitarian approach (greatest benefit for greatest number), life-cycle consideration (younger patients may receive ventilators over elderly to maximize life-years), fair innings, transparency, proportionality. Triage committees reduce bias." },
    { id:"p10q39", question:"Fidelity as a nursing ethical principle means:", options:["Being faithful to religious beliefs","Keeping promises and commitments to patients — being trustworthy and following through on obligations","Loyalty to hospital administration","Only following protocols exactly"], answer:1, explanation:"Fidelity: keeping promises, commitments, and being faithful to the trust placed in nursing. Includes: maintaining confidentiality, following through on care commitments, being honest, maintaining professional standards. Broken promises damage trust and therapeutic relationship." },
    { id:"p10q40", question:"The UAE's National Unified Number (NUN) or Emirates ID is required for:", options:["Only for UAE nationals","All residents and citizens — required for accessing healthcare services, including DHA-licensed facilities","Only for non-nationals","Only for insurance purposes"], answer:1, explanation:"Emirates ID (NUN): mandatory national identification for all UAE residents and citizens. Required for accessing government services, including SEHA (Abu Dhabi Health Services) and DHA-managed services. Facilitates unified health records and insurance verification." },
    { id:"p10q41", question:"Professional boundaries in the nurse-patient relationship are maintained by:", options:["Becoming personal friends with patients for better care","Maintaining therapeutic relationship — professional distance, not accepting gifts, no personal social media connections, not sharing personal information beyond therapeutic use","Ignoring patient boundaries","Being cold and distant always"], answer:1, explanation:"Professional boundaries: nurse-patient relationship is professional, not personal. Do not: accept significant gifts, have personal relationships outside healthcare setting, share personal contact information, connect on social media, self-disclose beyond therapeutic purpose. Protect patient from exploitation." },
    { id:"p10q42", question:"A patient in UAE requests their medical records. According to UAE law:", options:["Patients have no right to medical records","Patients have the right to access and receive copies of their medical records (Federal Law 4/2016 — Patient Rights Law)","Only family members can access records","Records are only available after 5 years"], answer:1, explanation:"UAE Patient Rights Law (Federal Law 4/2016): patients have the right to access their medical records, receive copies, and understand their health information. Requests handled per facility policy (usually within 2–3 working days). Some redactions may apply (third-party information)." },
    { id:"p10q43", question:"'Beneficence' conflicts with 'autonomy' when:", options:["There is no actual conflict possible","A patient refuses beneficial treatment — e.g., a competent Jehovah's Witness refusing blood transfusion","A physician orders medication","Two nurses disagree"], answer:1, explanation:"Beneficence-autonomy conflict: nurse wants to provide beneficial treatment but patient refuses (autonomy). Resolution: respect competent adult's autonomous refusal. Paternalistic override is generally unethical. Document, ensure informed refusal, continue other care." },
    { id:"p10q44", question:"The process of 'informed refusal' requires:", options:["Only patient signature","Ensuring the patient understands the consequences of refusing treatment, documenting their understanding, and that they have decision-making capacity — signed AMA (Against Medical Advice) form","Family agreement","Court approval always"], answer:1, explanation:"Informed refusal: patient must understand the specific risks of refusing (deterioration, death), have decision-making capacity, and refuse voluntarily. Document: information given, patient's understanding, capacity assessment, AMA form signed. Continue all other offered and accepted care." },
    { id:"p10q45", question:"The DHA's electronic health record system that enables information sharing across Dubai's health facilities is called:", options:["NABIDH (National Backbone for Integrated Dubai Health)","DAMAN","Al Jalila","NMC system"], answer:0, explanation:"NABIDH (National Backbone for Integrated Dubai Health): DHA's health information exchange platform. Integrates patient records across public and private health facilities in Dubai, enabling authorized healthcare providers to access patient history, medications, and test results." },
    { id:"p10q46", question:"Euthanasia is classified in UAE law as:", options:["Legally permitted with patient consent","Ethically permitted with family consent","Prohibited — constitutes homicide under UAE Penal Code and violates Islamic principles","Permitted for terminally ill patients only"], answer:2, explanation:"Euthanasia in UAE: illegal under UAE Penal Code (Article 302 — homicide). Also contrary to Islamic principles (sanctity of life, only Allah determines life and death). Palliative care and withdrawal of futile treatment are ethically and legally distinct from euthanasia." },
    { id:"p10q47", question:"The concept of 'futile treatment' in end-of-life care means:", options:["Any treatment the patient refuses","Treatment that cannot reasonably achieve its intended clinical goal — no realistic benefit possible","Experimental treatment","Any expensive treatment"], answer:1, explanation:"Futile treatment: treatment that cannot achieve its intended clinical goal, cannot restore reasonable quality of life, or merely prolongs dying. Ethics: withholding/withdrawing futile treatment is ethically distinct from euthanasia. DHA/hospital ethics committees assist in futility determinations." },
    { id:"p10q48", question:"Organ donation in the UAE is governed by:", options:["Voluntary consent only","Federal Law No. 5 of 2016 (on Organ Transplantation) — requires consent from deceased or family, donors can register through MOHAP","No legal framework","Only Islamic scholars decide"], answer:1, explanation:"UAE Organ Transplantation Law (Federal Law 5/2016): permits organ donation from deceased (brain-dead donor with family consent) and living donors (with conditions). MOHAP regulates transplant programs. Islamic scholars in UAE have approved organ donation as permissible (with conditions)." },
    { id:"p10q49", question:"A nurse discovers a medication error after the patient has been given the wrong drug. The CORRECT order of actions:", options:["Immediately document and ignore the patient","Assess patient condition, notify physician immediately, implement required treatment, document the error accurately (complete incident report), notify charge nurse/supervisor","Only document in personal notes","Warn colleagues to be careful"], answer:1, explanation:"Medication error response: 1) Patient safety first — assess for adverse effects, 2) Notify physician immediately, 3) Implement prescribed treatment for effects, 4) Accurate and complete documentation in medical record, 5) Complete incident report (non-punitive), 6) Notify supervisor." },
    { id:"p10q50", question:"Which HIPAA-equivalent regulation protects patient health information in the UAE?", options:["There is no health data protection law in UAE","UAE Federal Decree-Law 45/2021 (Data Protection Law) + Health Data Protection Guidelines from MOHAP/DHA protect patient health information","Only hospital internal policies","Only applies to electronic records"], answer:1, explanation:"UAE Data Protection: Federal Decree-Law 45/2021 (UAE PDPL) governs personal data including health data. DHA and MOHAP have specific health data guidelines. Health data is 'sensitive personal data' requiring explicit consent, proportionate use, and secure storage/sharing." },
    { id:"p10q51", question:"The ethical framework used in end-of-life care in Islamic context emphasizes:", options:["Euthanasia is acceptable","Sanctity of life — preservation of life is a duty, but extraordinary measures need not be used if no benefit; pain relief is permitted, care is obligatory","Life must be prolonged at all costs regardless of suffering","Family makes all decisions without patient or physician input"], answer:1, explanation:"Islamic bioethics (end of life): sanctity of life (hifz al-nafs — preservation of life), but futile treatment can be withheld/withdrawn. Prohibition of euthanasia. Pain relief (even if sedating) is permissible (doctrine of double effect). Care and comfort are obligatory even when cure is impossible." },
    { id:"p10q52", question:"Credentialing and privileging in UAE hospitals refers to:", options:["Hiring process for nurses","Process of verifying healthcare professionals' qualifications, experience, and competence — and granting specific clinical privileges appropriate to their skills","Salary determination","Performance appraisal"], answer:1, explanation:"Credentialing: verifying educational qualifications, training, licensure, references (primary source verification). Privileging: granting specific clinical privileges based on verified competencies. Required by DHA and JCI accreditation standards for all clinical staff." },
    { id:"p10q53", question:"Workplace violence prevention in UAE healthcare settings requires:", options:["Ignoring minor incidents","Zero-tolerance policy, staff training, reporting mechanisms, security measures — workplace violence is criminally prosecutable under UAE Penal Code","Only security guards","Accepting violence as part of nursing"],answer:1, explanation:"Workplace violence in healthcare: physical or verbal aggression toward health workers is prohibited. UAE Penal Code: assault is criminal. DHA requires: zero-tolerance policy, incident reporting, staff training in de-escalation, adequate security, legal prosecution of perpetrators." },
    { id:"p10q54", question:"Surrogacy is legal in the UAE:", options:["Yes — with medical supervision","Only for expats","No — surrogacy (including gestational surrogacy) is illegal in the UAE under Islamic law and UAE regulations","Only for citizens"], answer:2, explanation:"Surrogacy: ILLEGAL in UAE. Islamic law prohibits any form of surrogacy (child must be born to legally married couple's own gametes, carried by the wife). Any surrogacy arrangement (commercial or altruistic) is not recognized legally in UAE." },
    { id:"p10q55", question:"The nurse's role in clinical research (trials) includes ensuring:", options:["Research is conducted as quickly as possible","Informed consent is properly obtained, patient rights are protected, research protocol is followed, adverse events are reported — nurses are research advocates for patients","Only collecting data","Patients participate regardless of willingness"], answer:1, explanation:"Nursing role in research: patient advocacy — ensure informed consent is free and informed (not coerced), patients understand right to withdraw, adverse events reported to IRB/EC, protocol followed correctly, patient safety is prioritized over research objectives." },
    { id:"p10q56", question:"The principle of double effect permits:", options:["Intentionally causing harm for good outcomes","Administering appropriate pain medication (e.g., opioids) that may hasten death as a foreseeable but unintended side effect, when the primary intent is pain relief","Deliberate euthanasia","Any harmful action if benefits outweigh harms"], answer:1, explanation:"Doctrine of double effect: four conditions — 1) Act is good or neutral, 2) Good effect directly intended, 3) Bad effect not directly intended (foreseeable but unintended), 4) Good effect not achieved through bad effect, 5) Proportionate reason. Applies to palliative sedation for pain." },
    { id:"p10q57", question:"A nurse in Dubai suspects a child has been abused. The LEGAL obligation is:", options:["Discuss with parents first","Report immediately to child protective services/police — child protection is mandatory per Wadeema's Law (Federal Law 3/2016)","Only document findings","Wait for physician confirmation first"], answer:1, explanation:"Wadeema's Law (UAE Federal Law 3/2016 on child rights): all persons (including healthcare providers) who suspect child abuse or neglect MUST report to child protection authorities. Failure to report is a criminal offense. Report to police (999), Child Protection Center, or Ministry of Community Development." },
    { id:"p10q58", question:"'Cultural safety' in healthcare, especially in UAE's multicultural environment, means:", options:["Only hiring nurses from same culture as patients","Healthcare environment and practices that do not diminish, demean, or disempower the cultural identity and well-being of any individual","Only speaking patient's language","Ignoring cultural differences for standardization"], answer:1, explanation:"Cultural safety: healthcare delivered in a way that acknowledges and respects cultural identity, does not cause cultural harm, and empowers patients from all backgrounds to participate in their care. Includes: respectful communication, accommodation of practices (modesty, prayer times, dietary), family involvement." },
    { id:"p10q59", question:"Medical tourism patients in Dubai have the same patient rights as UAE residents under:", options:["Different rights — less protection","Same rights under DHA regulations and Federal Patient Rights Law — all patients in DHA-licensed facilities have equal rights","No rights if non-residents","Only emergency rights"], answer:1, explanation:"All patients in DHA-licensed facilities (regardless of nationality or residency status) are protected by UAE Patient Rights Law and DHA regulations. Healthcare providers have same duty of care. Medical records, consent, confidentiality apply equally." },
    { id:"p10q60", question:"The International Council of Nurses (ICN) Code of Ethics identifies four principal elements of nursing:", options:["Assessment, Planning, Implementation, Evaluation","Nurses and People, Nurses and Practice, Nurses and Profession, Nurses and Co-workers","Safety, Quality, Ethics, Law","Care, Compassion, Competence, Communication"], answer:1, explanation:"ICN Code of Ethics (2021 revision): four elements — 1) Nurses and People (patient-centered care, dignity), 2) Nurses and Practice (professional standards, competence), 3) Nurses and the Profession (advancing profession, research), 4) Nurses and Global Health (sustainability, equity)." },
    { id:"p10q61", question:"Resource allocation in ICU (ventilators, beds) should be based on:", options:["Patient's ability to pay","First come, first served always","Clinical need, expected benefit, and fair process — guided by written institutional triage policies and ethics committee","Physician preference alone"], answer:2, explanation:"ICU resource allocation: primary criterion: clinical benefit (who will benefit most from the resource). Secondary: expected outcomes. Transparent, consistent, written protocols and ethics committee involvement reduce bias and ensure fairness." },
    { id:"p10q62", question:"The legal document that designates someone to make medical decisions when a person lacks capacity is:", options:["Will (inheritance)","Durable Power of Attorney for Healthcare / Healthcare Proxy","Living will (advance directive)","Insurance policy"], answer:1, explanation:"Healthcare proxy/durable power of attorney for healthcare: designates a specific person (agent/surrogate) to make medical decisions when the patient lacks decision-making capacity. Different from advance directive (which states specific wishes). UAE: limited formal legal framework, family typically serves as surrogate." },
    { id:"p10q63", question:"Whistle-blower protection in UAE healthcare means:", options:["There is no protection for whistle-blowers","DHA and UAE law provide some protections for healthcare workers who report patient safety concerns or violations in good faith","Whistle-blowers are always punished","Only physicians are protected"], answer:1, explanation:"UAE whistleblower protections: DHA has a confidential reporting mechanism for patient safety concerns. UAE anti-corruption laws (Federal Law 6/2012) provide some protections. Healthcare workers should use internal channels first, then DHA/external bodies. Good faith reporting is encouraged." },
    { id:"p10q64", question:"The principle of 'justice as fairness' (Rawls) applied to healthcare means:", options:["The strongest get resources","Healthcare resources should be allocated to most benefit the least advantaged members of society — reduce health inequity","Each person gets exactly equal resources","Pay-to-play system"], answer:1, explanation:"Rawlsian justice: design systems from behind the 'veil of ignorance' — not knowing your position in society. Applied to health: prioritize needs of most vulnerable/disadvantaged, reduce health inequities. Basis for universal health coverage advocacy." },
    { id:"p10q65", question:"Moral distress in nursing occurs when:", options:["A nurse is physically tired","A nurse knows the ethically correct action but is unable to carry it out due to institutional or situational constraints","A nurse makes a medication error","A nurse disagrees with a patient's choice"], answer:1, explanation:"Moral distress: knowing the right thing to do ethically but being prevented by institutional constraints, hierarchies, or system factors. Leads to emotional distress, burnout, and compassion fatigue. Moral residue: unresolved moral distress that accumulates over time. Addressed by ethics support, peer discussion, leadership support." },
    { id:"p10q66", question:"The nurse is asked to participate in a procedure they believe is ethically wrong. The nurse can exercise:", options:["No rights — must follow orders","Conscientious objection — the right to refrain from participating in procedures that violate deeply held moral beliefs, if patient safety is ensured by alternative arrangements","Only after shift ends","Only if supported by other nurses"], answer:1, explanation:"Conscientious objection: nurses have the right to refuse participation in procedures against their moral or religious beliefs (e.g., abortion, euthanasia — where legal). Must notify in advance, must not abandon patient, must ensure alternative care is arranged. Cannot conscientiously object to emergency care." },
    { id:"p10q67", question:"Malpractice insurance (professional liability insurance) for nurses in UAE:", options:["Is not required","Is required by DHA for licensed nurses — protects against financial consequences of malpractice claims","Only covers physical injuries","Only needed for physicians"], answer:1, explanation:"DHA licensure requirement: nurses must provide proof of professional liability (malpractice) insurance. Protects nurse and patient in event of malpractice claim. Some employers (DHA hospitals) provide this; private practitioners must obtain their own." },
    { id:"p10q68", question:"The 'standard of care' in nursing malpractice is determined by:", options:["What the individual nurse usually does","What a reasonably competent nurse with similar training and experience would do in the same circumstances","The hospital's specific policies only","What the physician orders"], answer:1, explanation:"Standard of care: what a reasonably competent nurse with equivalent training, experience, and specialty would do in the same situation. Established through: nursing standards (ICN, nursing associations), facility policies, expert witness testimony, published guidelines." },
    { id:"p10q69", question:"The SBAR communication tool in healthcare stands for:", options:["Safety, Background, Assessment, Review","Situation, Background, Assessment, Recommendation — structured clinical communication tool","Summary, Brief, Action, Response","Status, Background, Action, Result"], answer:1, explanation:"SBAR (situation-background-assessment-recommendation): standardized communication framework used in clinical handover, escalation of concerns, and team communication. Reduces communication errors — major cause of adverse events. Widely required in JCI-accredited UAE hospitals." },
    { id:"p10q70", question:"Palliative care in UAE healthcare aims to:", options:["Hasten death","Replace all curative treatment","Improve quality of life of patients and families facing life-threatening illness — through pain relief, symptom management, and psychological/spiritual support — alongside curative treatment","Only provide emotional support"], answer:2, explanation:"WHO palliative care definition: improves QoL for patients/families facing life-threatening illness through prevention and relief of suffering by early identification, impeccable assessment, and treatment of pain and other problems — physical, psychological, spiritual. Provided alongside (not instead of) curative treatment." },
    { id:"p10q71", question:"Breach of confidentiality is justified when:", options:["Hospital administration requests information","A serious, credible, and imminent threat to an identifiable third party exists — Tarasoff duty to warn","A colleague is curious","Media requests information"], answer:1, explanation:"Tarasoff principle (duty to warn): if patient discloses intent to harm specific identifiable person, clinician has duty to warn that person AND report to authorities. Applies in UAE where public safety overrides confidentiality. Also applies for notifiable disease contacts." },
    { id:"p10q72", question:"Electronic medical records (EMR) in UAE hospitals must:", options:["Be accessible to anyone who requests them","Be secure, password-protected, with access limited to treatment team, audit trails of all accesses, backed up regularly — per DHA and UAE data protection regulations","Be deleted after discharge","Be shared freely with insurance companies"], answer:1, explanation:"EMR security requirements: role-based access control (only treatment team), strong authentication, audit trails of all access, encrypted storage and transmission, regular backups, disaster recovery. UAE data protection law requires breach notification within 72 hours of discovery." },
    { id:"p10q73", question:"The ethical concept of 'autonomy' is limited when:", options:["It is never limited","The exercise of autonomy harms other identifiable third parties (harm principle — Mill) or when decision-making capacity is impaired","Doctors disagree with the patient","Family objects to patient's decision"], answer:1, explanation:"Autonomy limits: 1) Harm to others (e.g., refusing isolation for TB — public health can override), 2) Impaired decision-making capacity (then surrogate decision-maker), 3) Emergency (unconscious patient — presumed consent for treatment). Competent adult's autonomy is otherwise respected." },
    { id:"p10q74", question:"The DHA Smart Licensing system allows nurses to:", options:["Only check license expiry date","Manage licensing online: apply, renew, update information, pay fees, check CPD status, receive notifications — reducing bureaucratic burden","Only for Emirati nurses","Only for administrative staff"], answer:1, explanation:"DHA Smart Licensing: digital platform for all DHA-licensed healthcare professionals to manage licensure online. Features: application, renewal, CPD tracking, Good Standing Certificate requests, specialization change, and verification by employers." },
    { id:"p10q75", question:"A nurse in Dubai discovers that a colleague is diverting (stealing) patient medications. The nurse must:", options:["Ignore it — not their responsibility","Report immediately to supervisor and pharmacy — this is patient safety issue AND criminal offense in UAE (drug diversion under Federal Anti-Narcotics Law)","Confront the colleague privately first","Wait to see if it continues"], answer:1, explanation:"Drug diversion: criminal offense under UAE Federal Law 14/1995 (drugs and narcotics). Nurse has legal and ethical duty to report immediately: supervisor, pharmacy, risk management. Failure to report is itself a violation. Patient safety and drug supply integrity are at risk." },
    { id:"p10q76", question:"The role of the hospital ethics committee (HEC) in UAE hospitals is:", options:["Making clinical treatment decisions","Advisory role: case consultation for complex ethical dilemmas, policy development, staff education in ethics — does not replace clinical decision-making","Disciplinary body for staff","Legal authority over patient care"], answer:1, explanation:"HEC (Hospital Ethics Committee): multidisciplinary body providing ethical consultation and guidance. Functions: case consultations (end-of-life, resource allocation, consent disputes), develop ethics policies, educate staff. Advisory — final decisions remain with patient/family and clinical team." },
    { id:"p10q77", question:"Family presence during resuscitation (CPR) in UAE hospitals:", options:["Is always prohibited","Is increasingly supported as patient/family right — many DHA hospitals allow family presence with staff support during resuscitation","Is only for pediatric patients","Is mandatory by law"], answer:1, explanation:"Family presence during resuscitation: evidence shows family presence does not compromise resuscitation and may help family grieve and accept outcome. Many UAE hospitals (following international recommendations) allow it with a designated family support staff member. Cultural sensitivity is essential." },
    { id:"p10q78", question:"Which international agreement commits UAE to global health initiatives?", options:["Only bilateral agreements","WHO Constitution (UAE member state) — commits to WHO guidelines, International Health Regulations (IHR 2005), SDG commitments, and health diplomacy","No international health commitments","Only Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) health agreements"], answer:1, explanation:"UAE WHO membership: commits to WHO guidelines, reports notifiable diseases (IHR 2005), contributes to global health governance, adopts WHO recommendations. Also member of GCC health coordination, UN SDG 3, and participates in global health security agenda." },
    { id:"p10q79", question:"A patient with dementia lacks decision-making capacity. Medical decisions are made by:", options:["The treating nurse","The patient's legal guardian, appointed next-of-kin, or court-appointed guardian — in hierarchical order per UAE law","The most senior physician alone","Any staff member"], answer:1, explanation:"Surrogate decision-making in UAE: legal guardian (court-appointed), spouse, adult children, parents — in hierarchical order. Surrogate applies 'substituted judgment' standard (what patient would have wanted) or 'best interests' standard if patient's wishes unknown. Healthcare team guides family." },
    { id:"p10q80", question:"The term 'iatrogenic' in healthcare refers to:", options:["Patient-caused harm","Harm caused by medical treatment or healthcare provider — from Greek: iatros (healer) + genic (causing)","Environmental illness","Infectious disease"], answer:1, explanation:"Iatrogenic illness: illness caused by medical intervention (drugs, procedures, infections from healthcare setting). Examples: drug adverse effects, surgical complications, CAUTI, CLABSI. Reducing iatrogenic harm is a patient safety priority. 'First, do no harm' applies." },
    { id:"p10q81", question:"The 'Safe Surgery Saves Lives' WHO initiative requires implementation of:", options:["Only post-operative care","Surgical safety checklist (Sign-in, Time-out, Sign-out) — mandatory in JCI-accredited UAE hospitals","Only anesthesia protocols","Only sterility protocols"], answer:1, explanation:"WHO Surgical Safety Checklist: Sign-in (before anesthesia), Time-out (before incision — full team confirms patient identity, site, procedure, consent, allergies, equipment), Sign-out (before patient leaves OR). Reduces surgical deaths by 47%, complications by 36%. Mandatory in JCI hospitals." },
    { id:"p10q82", question:"National Patient Safety Goals (NPSGs) or equivalents in DHA/JCI-accredited UAE hospitals include:", options:["Only hand hygiene","Correct patient identification (2 identifiers), medication safety, communication (SBAR/read-back), infection prevention, fall prevention, pressure injury prevention","Only surgical safety","Only medication safety"], answer:1, explanation:"JCI/DHA Patient Safety Goals (aligned with WHO Global Patient Safety Challenge): 2-identifier patient ID, safe surgery checklist, medication reconciliation, hand hygiene, fall prevention, pressure ulcer prevention, communication handoff standards (SBAR), sepsis recognition." },
    { id:"p10q83", question:"The principle of 'respect for persons' (from the Belmont Report) in research ethics includes:", options:["Only informed consent","Autonomy (informed consent) and Protection of persons with diminished autonomy (children, prisoners, cognitively impaired) — extra protections required","Only beneficence","Only justice"], answer:1, explanation:"Belmont Report (1979) — three principles for research involving humans: Respect for Persons (autonomy + protection of vulnerable), Beneficence (maximize benefit, minimize harm), Justice (fair distribution of research burdens/benefits). Foundation of research ethics globally." },
    { id:"p10q84", question:"Horizontal violence (lateral violence/bullying) in nursing:", options:["Is acceptable as 'nurses eat their young'","Is unethical and harmful — includes verbal abuse, withholding information, sabotage between colleagues — DHA and UAE labor law prohibit workplace harassment","Is only a problem in some countries","Should be reported to no one"], answer:1, explanation:"Horizontal violence (nurse-to-nurse bullying): significant problem affecting retention, patient safety, and nurse well-being. UAE Labor Law prohibits workplace harassment. DHA requires facilities to have zero-tolerance policies and formal reporting mechanisms. Bystander intervention is encouraged." },
    { id:"p10q85", question:"The nurse's responsibility for continuing professional development (CPD) in UAE (DHA):", options:["CPD is optional","DHA requires minimum CPD hours for license renewal — nurses must complete approved CPD activities and maintain records","Only required for senior nurses","Only required every 10 years"], answer:1, explanation:"DHA CPD requirements: nurses must complete required CPD hours (typically 30 hours per 2-year license period) through DHA-approved programs. CPD includes: conferences, courses, online learning, clinical training, research. Records maintained in DHA Smart Licensing system." },
    { id:"p10q86", question:"Which legal concept protects nurses who act in good faith in an emergency?", options:["There is no protection","Good Samaritan law — provides immunity from civil liability when acting in good faith in an emergency outside one's formal employment without expectation of payment","Malpractice insurance only","Only DHA license provides protection"], answer:1, explanation:"Good Samaritan protection: protects healthcare professionals who provide emergency aid in good faith (e.g., at accident scene) without expectation of payment from civil liability for unintentional harm. UAE has limited explicit Good Samaritan legislation; encourage duty to assist (moral obligation)." },
    { id:"p10q87", question:"Reproductive technologies (IVF) in UAE are regulated and must be:", options:["Provided to all regardless of marital status","Only performed for married Muslim couples with legal marriage documentation — strict Islamic ethical requirements apply","Available to same-sex couples","Provided without any restrictions"], answer:1, explanation:"UAE IVF regulation (Federal Law 11/2008): permitted ONLY for legally married couples. Gametes must be from legal husband and wife. Sperm/egg donation from third parties is prohibited. Surrogacy prohibited. Embryos from the legal couple can be frozen for future use by same couple." },
    { id:"p10q88", question:"The duty of a nurse to maintain professional competence means:", options:["Only completing initial education","Continuously updating knowledge and skills, recognizing and working within personal competence limits, seeking supervision when needed, and participating in CPD — a lifelong professional obligation","Only attending mandatory training","Competence is only assessed at licensing exam"], answer:1, explanation:"Maintaining competence: ICN Code of Ethics and DHA licensing requirements mandate nurses to maintain and improve clinical competence throughout career, practice only within areas of competence, disclose limitations, seek help when needed, and participate in continuing education and quality improvement." },
    { id:"p10q89", question:"When a DHA nurse's license expires during employment:", options:["They can continue working until renewal","They must STOP practicing immediately — practicing with an expired license is illegal and grounds for serious disciplinary action","Only their hospital can authorize continuation","They have a 6-month grace period automatically"], answer:1, explanation:"Practicing without a valid DHA license: illegal in Dubai. Both the nurse and the facility that allows unlicensed practice face serious penalties (fines, closure, criminal charges). Nurses must renew 90 days before expiry and cannot practice from the expiry date until renewal is confirmed." },
    { id:"p10q90", question:"The concept of 'distributive justice' in healthcare resource allocation means:", options:["Giving everyone equal amounts of everything","Fair allocation of healthcare resources based on need, potential benefit, and fair process — considering equity (not just equality)","Rich patients get more resources","Patients pay for what they receive"], answer:1, explanation:"Distributive justice: fairness in allocating healthcare resources. Criteria include: medical need, equal access, ability to benefit, contribution to society (controversial), life-years (controversial). Equity (giving more to those with greater need) differs from equality (giving same to all)." },
    { id:"p10q91", question:"Nursing handover (shift report) has ethical obligations including:", options:["Speed is the priority — brevity over accuracy","Accurate, complete information transfer — omitting information that leads to patient harm constitutes negligence; use standardized handover tool (SBAR/I-PASS)","Sharing only positive information","Only verbal report with no documentation"], answer:1, explanation:"Nursing handover ethics: accurate and complete transfer of patient information is a professional and legal obligation. ISBAR/SBAR, I-PASS, or ISOBAR structured tools reduce omissions. Incomplete handover leading to patient harm = negligence. Documentation of handover is mandatory." },
    { id:"p10q92", question:"Which religious consideration is most commonly encountered in UAE healthcare?", options:["Only Christian values","Islamic principles — prayer times (Salah), fasting (Ramadan), gender-segregated care, halal medications, end-of-life principles, family decision-making structure","Only Hindu dietary restrictions","Only Jewish dietary laws"], answer:1, explanation:"UAE healthcare Islamic considerations: prayer accommodation (time, direction — Qibla, ablution facilities), Ramadan fasting (medication timing, IV nutrition in emergencies), gender preferences (same-gender care), halal medications (gelatin source), Islamic end-of-life principles, family-centered decision-making." },
    { id:"p10q93", question:"The UAE's 'Vision 2021' and 'UAE Vision 2031' national health goals include:", options:["Reducing all healthcare spending","Universal health coverage, reducing lifestyle disease burden, improving quality of care, developing health infrastructure and UAE national healthcare workforce","Only building new hospitals","Privatizing all healthcare"], answer:1, explanation:"UAE Vision: achieve universal health coverage, reduce burden of NCDs (obesity, diabetes, CVD), improve preventive healthcare, develop medical education and UAE national healthcare professionals (Emiratization), achieve international healthcare accreditation standards, and medical tourism leadership." },
    { id:"p10q94", question:"Telemedicine and digital health in UAE are regulated by:", options:["No regulatory framework exists","DHA Digital Health Strategy and telehealth guidelines — specific regulations for telemedicine platforms, data security, valid prescriptions, cross-border practice","Only Ministry of Economy","Individual hospitals set their own rules"], answer:1, explanation:"DHA Digital Health: issued telemedicine regulations during COVID-19 (2020) and continuing. Requirements: DHA-licensed platforms, licensed practitioners, informed consent, EMR integration, data security, prescription regulations, clear scope of practice. Telehealth rapidly expanding in UAE post-pandemic." },
    { id:"p10q95", question:"The International Patient Safety Classification (IPSC) by WHO defines a 'near miss' as:", options:["A sentinel event causing patient harm","An incident that did NOT reach the patient (caught before reaching patient) — important for learning and prevention","A minor medication error","Any documentation error"], answer:1, explanation:"Near miss (close call): event that could have caused harm but did NOT reach the patient due to chance or intervention. Near misses are reported and analyzed to prevent future actual harm. Encouraging near-miss reporting (non-punitive culture) is essential for patient safety." },
    { id:"p10q96", question:"In UAE, a nurse accused of malpractice can be subject to:", options:["Criminal prosecution only","DHA disciplinary action (license suspension/revocation), civil compensation claims (UAE Medical Liability Law 4/2016), and potentially criminal prosecution for gross negligence","Only hospital termination","Only civil claims"], answer:1, explanation:"Nurse malpractice consequences in UAE: 1) DHA disciplinary proceedings (warning, suspension, license conditions, revocation), 2) Civil liability (compensation to patient under Medical Liability Law), 3) Criminal prosecution (for intentional harm or gross negligence constituting a crime under UAE Penal Code)." },
    { id:"p10q97", question:"The concept of 'informed consent by proxy' applies when:", options:["The patient is from another country","The patient lacks decision-making capacity — a legal guardian or surrogate makes decisions based on patient's known wishes or best interests","Two physicians must agree","The patient is elderly"], answer:1, explanation:"Proxy/surrogate consent: when patient lacks decision-making capacity (unconscious, dementia, severe psychiatric illness, minors). Surrogate hierarchy: legal guardian > spouse > adult children > parents > siblings > extended family. Standard: substituted judgment (patient's known wishes) preferred over best interests." },
    { id:"p10q98", question:"Healthcare worker rights in UAE include:", options:["No specific rights","Safe working conditions, reasonable hours, protection from violence, non-discrimination, confidentiality of health information, ability to refuse participation in procedures against conscience","Working unlimited hours","No protection from workplace violence"], answer:1, explanation:"UAE healthcare worker rights (UAE Labor Law + professional codes): safe workplace, defined working hours, protection from violence (UAE Penal Code), anti-discrimination, confidentiality of own health data, reasonable accommodation for religious practices, and conscientious objection rights." },
    { id:"p10q99", question:"Patient safety culture in a healthcare organization is best described as:", options:["Blaming individuals for errors","A blame-free environment where errors are reported openly, analyzed for system causes, and used for learning — leadership commitment to safety is foundational","Hiding errors from leadership","Punishing anyone involved in near misses"], answer:1, explanation:"Safety culture (James Reason): just culture — not blame-free (accountability for reckless behavior) but blame-wise (system analysis, not individual witch-hunt). Components: psychological safety to report, leadership commitment, learning from errors, teamwork, communication. Measured by patient safety culture surveys." },
    { id:"p10q100", question:"The DHA's mission in healthcare regulation is best described as:", options:["Only collecting licensing fees","Regulating, licensing, and monitoring healthcare services to achieve the highest levels of quality, patient safety, and access to healthcare for all people in Dubai — ensuring a world-class healthcare system","Building hospitals only","Managing only government health facilities"], answer:1, explanation:"DHA Mission: to lead, license, and regulate the healthcare sector in Dubai to ensure the highest standards of healthcare for the population. Includes: licensing, quality and patient safety, health planning, public health programs, emergency preparedness, and health information management." }
  ]
};
export default phase10;
